body:
As a TRE admin I have added frewall.tf file under <i>AzureTRE/templates/workspaces/base/terrafrom/ </i> folder with the following content:
```
locals { 
  service_id = "970b"
  workspace_id = substr(var.tre_resource_id, -4, -1)
  allowed_urls                     = ["#####.blob.core.windows.net/","*google.com"]
  service_resource_name_suffix    = "${var.tre_id}-ws-${local.workspace_id}-svc-${local.service_id}"
}

data "azurerm_firewall" "fw" {
  name                = "fw-${var.tre_id}"
  resource_group_name = "rg-${var.tre_id}"
}

data "azurerm_virtual_network" "ws" {
    name                = "vnet-${var.tre_id}-ws-${local.workspace_id}"
    resource_group_name = azurerm_resource_group.ws.name
}

resource "null_resource" "az_login" {
  provisioner "local-exec" {
    command = "az login --identity -u '${var.arm_client_id}'"
  }

  triggers = {
    timestamp = timestamp()
  }
}

data "external" "rule_priorities" {
  program = ["bash", "-c", "./get_firewall_priorities.sh"]

  query = {
    firewall_name       = data.azurerm_firewall.fw.name
    resource_group_name = data.azurerm_firewall.fw.resource_group_name
    service_resource_name_suffix = local.service_resource_name_suffix
  }
  depends_on = [
    null_resource.az_login
  ]
}

resource "azurerm_firewall_application_rule_collection" "apprulecollection" {
  name                = "arc-${local.service_resource_name_suffix}"
  azure_firewall_name = data.azurerm_firewall.fw.name
  resource_group_name = data.azurerm_firewall.fw.resource_group_name
  priority            = data.external.rule_priorities.result.application_rule_priority
  action              = "Allow"

  rule {
    name = "allowRulesTest"

    source_addresses = data.azurerm_virtual_network.ws.address_space

    target_fqdns = local.allowed_urls

    protocol {
      port = "443"
      type = "Https"
    }
    protocol {
      port = "80"
      type = "Http"
    }
  }
}
```

The workspace was re-built using make <b>workspace_bundle BUNDLE=base </b>command

We cannot see this rule anywhere within firewall policy Rule Connections.
We cannot connect to google in a virtual desktop, power shell results in Request timed out

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/107872721/222758972-7c466323-027e-4251-9acf-cf2bdb25f8da.png)

The excersise was to access azure AD from the virtual machine.

**Describe the bug**

E2E tests fail

> assert (template_name in response.json()["templateNames"]), f"No ***template_name*** template found" 
> KeyError: 'templateNames'

GET/api/workspace-templates
Get Workspace Template Names returns:
    
```JSON        
{
  "templates": [
    {
      "name": "tre-workspace-vanilla",
      "description": "vanilla workspace bundle"
    },
    {
      "name": "tre-workspace-azureml-devtestlabs",
      "description": "Azure ML and Dev Test Labs custom parameters"
    },
    {
      "name": "tre-workspace-innereye-deeplearning",
      "description": "InnerEye Deep Learning Workspace custom parameters"
    },
    {
      "name": "tre-workspace-innereye-deeplearning-inference",
      "description": "InnerEye Deep Learning and Inference Workspace custom parameters"
    }
  ]
}
```
it used to return:

```JSON   
{
  "templateNames": [
    "tre-workspace-azureml-devtestlabs",
    "tre-workspace-innereye-deeplearning-inference",
    "tre-workspace-innereye-deeplearning",
    "tre-workspace-vanilla"
  ]
}
```

**Describe the bug**
When deploying a workspace such as `workspaces/azureml_devtestlabs` that requires `acr_name` deployment fails.

Two issues:
1. The API should validate the parameter and say it cannot be found as is marked as required
2. The API should inject this parameter as it is system provided

**Steps to reproduce**
1. Publish  `workspaces/azureml_devtestlabs` bundle
1. Deploy the bundle via the create workspace API with a payload without acr_name:

```
{
  "displayName": "My workspace",
  "description": "workspace for team X",
  "workspaceType": "tre-workspace-azureml-devtestlabs",
  "parameters": {
"address_space": "192.168.11.0/24"},
  "authConfig": {
    "provider": "AAD",
    "data": {
      "app_id": "xxxx"
    }
  }
}
```

When the connection to Azure Cosmos Db is okay, but the connection to Azure Service Bus is not, the status endpoint incorrectly responds with:
```Json
{
  "services": [
    {
      "service": "Cosmos DB",
      "status": "Not OK",
      "message": "State Store endpoint is not responding"
    }
  ]
}
```
